description.narrative:
Life & Peace Institute’s (LPI) Inclusive Peace in Practice initiative (IPIP) seeks to develop and test new models for making international peace policies less remote to, and more influenced by, the everyday experiences of those living in conflict. It is a four-year initiative, with a 15-month inception period from October 2018 to December 2019 devoted to gather and generate learning on the nature of the core challenge, and the potential for new and effective solutions – from within LPI and from external actors, in and outside of peacebuilding, at local and global levels.
The annual report for 2019 shows that all deliverable under the three inception work strands were achieved within the time frame outlined in the 2019 annual plan, with the exception of the stock-taking exercise of LPI’s current policy engagement efforts across the Institute (Activity 6.1.1b) which started in autumn 2019 and which will culminate in 2020. 
As an Initiative with global reach, the work took place in eight countries on three continents, encompassing engagement with over 310 unique individuals and approximately 110 organisations and institutions, both public and private. The following was achieved: 
- Inception workshops provided space for peacebuilding practitioners working in/on situations of protracted conflict to provide input to the initiative;
- Reflections on LPI’s previous bottom-up policy engagement generated new lines of enquiry;
- An assessment of global peacebuilding advocacy priorities and approaches increased knowledge of the functioning of the peace sector and validated the initiative internationally; 
- A multi-stakeholder Power Analysis illuminated the ways in which both the external environment and LPI itself influences prospects for greater local inclusion; 
- A Discourse Analysis explored how the way in which the international peacebuilding architecture talks influences what it does in practice, and regulates which stakeholders control its direction;
- Eight consultation validations provided opportunities to share key findings and emerging insights from the first phase of the inception journey, assess whether they resonated with a diverse range of external actors and how they could be sharpened, and discuss where there was momentum for change and;
- An Inclusive Peace Lab brought a broad range of actors together to help nuance our understanding of the inception’s analysis, identify where there is energy for action, and design strategies to begin to shift the system.
In addition to the main deliverables, LPI made investments in external relationship-building, internal synergising, conceptualising communication products and setting-up the operational parameters for the Initiative. The majority of the inception activities were developed and implemented in close collaboration with other LPI programmes and units. The creation of these cross-organisational spaces has been one of the key added values of IPIP to LPI programmes. All of the above paved way for the IPIP programme 2020-22.
